s=Step.new(recipe_id: 636, step: "To make the cake: Heat oven to 300. Line the bottom of 2 - 9 cake pans with parchment paper. In the bowl of stand mixer with the whisk attachment add the cocoa and boiling water. Whisk on low until smooth. Add the butter and sour cream and blend on low until the butter is melted. Let cool for a few minutes if still very hot. Add eggs and vanilla. On medium speed blend until very smooth. Cool for 10 minutes. While the cocoa mixture is cooling sift together the flours sugar baking soda and salt. With the mixer on low add the dry ingredients to the cocoa mixture a little at a time. Scrape down the sides a couple of times. Increase the mixer speed to high and blend for 3 minutes. Divide the batter evenly between the cake pans using a kitchen scale if you have one or scoop with a measuring cup if not. Gently shake the pans so that the batter is smooth across the top. Bake on the center rack of your oven until the cake is firm in the middle and pulling away from the edges a bit. About 45 minutes - 1 hour. Cool completely on a cooling rack preferably overnight as it will make splitting them into layers easier if they have firmed up a bit. To make the frosting: In the bowl of a stand mixer with the whisk attachment add the eggs and whisk on medium high until frothy. Add 6 Tbs of sugar and beat on high to medium peaks. It will be smooth and shiny and the peaks will curl a little. Stop the mixer. In a heavy bottomed medium saucepan over medium high heat add cup + 2 Tbs sugar and corn syrup. Cook while stirring gently until the sugar begins to melt then stop stirring and bring to a rolling boil. Remove from the heat. Turn the mixer on medium high. Slowly and steadily pour the syrup in keeping your stream on the edge of the bowl as to not allow it to touch the whisk. Do not scrape residual sugar out of the pan. Whisk on medium for 7 minutes. Add the butter 1 Tbs at a time. Scrape down the sides and add the melted chocolate. Blend until smooth and creamy scraping down the sides another time or two. To make the raspberry filling: In a small bowl stir together the raspberry jam and liquor until well blended. Assembly: Use a long serrated knife to carefully split the cakes in half. Slowly rotate the cake as you are slicing towards the center to ensure an even split. Place the bottom layer crumb side down on a flat serving platter or a cake stand lined with wax or parchment paper to help keep it clean while frosting and garnishing. Top the bottom layer with about 1 cups of frosting. Spread it evenly with a cake spatula to just shy of the cakes edge. Spread 1/3 of the raspberry jam mixture on top of the smooth side of the second layer of that cake. Carefully place it on top of the frosted layer jam side down. Repeat with the next two layers but be sure that the top layer has the smooth side up for the final frosting. Spoon about cup of the frosting into a small bowl. Spread it very thinly all over the cake top and sides with a cake spatula. You will be able to see the layers through this layer of frosting called a crumb coat. The crumb coat seals in cake crumbs so they dont mix in with the thicker final layer of frosting. Chill the cake for 20 minutes or until the crumb coat is firm. Do not refrigerate the remaining frosting while chilling. Scrape the remaining frosting onto the top of the cake. Spread evenly over the top and sides of the cake with a cake spatula. The finish will not be perfect but be sure to cover completely and uniformly. You dont want to be able to distinguish the layers from underneath the frosting. With the back of a teaspoon create little waves and flips over the top of the cake. To garnish: Working over a large surface area to catch the excess take handfuls of the chocolate chips and gently pat them into the sides of the cake. Remove the excess chips from your platter/cake plate. Cut away the excess wax/parchment paper by outlining the edge of the bottom of the cake by pressing the tip of a very sharp pairing knife through the paper. Once youve gone completely around the cake cut through the edge of the paper to the edge of the cake and then carefully pull the excess paper from around the cake. Arrange raspberries on the top of the cake.")
s.save!
s=Step.new(recipe_id: 637, step: "Step 1 Preheat the oven to 375. Line large rimmed baking sheet with parchment paper. Step 2 Arrange the bacon slices on the paper in a single layer. Stir orange marmalade; brush over one side of bacon. Bake for 15 to 20 minutes or until sizzling and browned. Transfer the bacon to paper towels glazed side up to drain and cool slightly. Cut each bacon piece in half to fit size of bun. Step 3 3.Meanwhile prepare buns according to package directions. (If you cannot find steam buns here is an alternative: Using the grand size canned biscuit dough press each into a 5-inch round. Brush one side of each flattened biscuit with some canola oil. Fold each biscuit gently in half oiled sides together. In deep skillet or wok heat 1/2 to 1 inch water (water should not touch bottom of buns). Spray stainless steel steamer baskets with no-stick cooking spray; place in skillet. Arrange each folded biscuits on a square of parchment paper at least 1 inch apart in steamer basket. Cover; cook over medium-low heat 15 to 20 minutes or until no longer doughy.) Step 4 In small bowl combine scallions chili and vinegar; set aside. Step 5 To assemble: Unfold each biscuit and layer with some hoisin sauce lettuce and bacon. Sprinkle bacon with toasted sesame seeds. Add desired amount of scallions and chili. Serve warm. Garnish platter with oranges.")
