s=Step.new(recipe_id: 638, step: "Step 1: Crust Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Lightly grease a 9 1/2 inch Pyrex pie plate. In medium bowl combine biscotti crumbs 1 tablespoon unsweetened cocoa powder and 2 teaspoons sugar stir in melted butter. Pat into bottom and slightly up sides of prepared pie plate. Bake crust for 13-15 minutes cool. Step 2: Mousse In a medium chilled bowl whip 1 1/2 cups heavy cream with hand held mixer until peaks start to form refrigerate until needed. Combine 2 tablespoons sugar with 1/4 cup of water in small saucepan and bring to boil. While syrup is boiling beat egg yolks in large bowl of stand mixer (fitted with whisk attachment) on low speed. Gradually pour in the boiling syrup and increase speed to high and whisk until mixture is pale yellow and doubled in volume about 5 minutes. Slowly add in the melted chocolate and 1/2 teaspoon Frangelico and whisk until well blended. Remove whipped cream from refrigerator and gently fold into the chocolate mixture into about 3 batches being careful not to deflate volume. Pour into cooled biscotti crust and refrigerate 2 hours or overnight before topping pie. Step 3: Topping In a medium chilled bowl whip 1 cup heavy cream with 1/2 teaspoon Frangelico until stiff peaks form. Fill a pastry bag (using tip of choice) with whipped cream. Remove pie from refrigerator and pipe whipped cream over top of pie. If desired garnish pie with biscotti crumbs cocoa powder and chocolate decorations or shaved chocolate. Serve; store pie in refrigerator.")
s.save!
s=Step.new(recipe_id: 639, step: "Directions: Boil chicken until cooked through. Reserve 2 cups of the water. Shred the chicken. In a large pot combine all of the ingredients (including the 2 cups of reserved chicken water) EXCEPT for the corn cream cheese and instant rice. Stir. Simmer for 1 1/2 hours stirring occasionally. Add corn and instant rice. Cook an addional 30 minutes. Stir in cream cheese and stir until melted. Top with cheese and/or tortilla chips. Enjoy. Note: Also does well in the crock pot. The longer it cooks the more the flavor come out.")
